projects: [{'title': "Literature study tittled: ''Wastewater Based Epidemiology- a useful complementary method to Human Biomonitoring for evaluation of human exposure to pollutants''", 'date': {'start': {'month': 6, 'day': None, 'year': 2021}, 'end': {'month': 8, 'day': None, 'year': 2021}}, 'description': 'The goals of this literature study were to explain why wastewater based epidemiology (WBE) would be a good additional tool to human biomonitoring (HBM) for assessing human exposure to pollutants, review WBE’s applicability to 7 pollutant categories, discuss wastewater analytical methods and challenges of wastewater analysis and finally, to give ideas on how to design an ideal experiment combining WBE and HBM.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Foteini', 'last_name': 'Eleftheriadou', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Analytical Chemist'}]}, {'title': 'Development of SPE-LC-MS/MS methods for thyroid hormones in cell lysate', 'date': {'start': {'month': 9, 'day': None, 'year': 2020}, 'end': {'month': 6, 'day': None, 'year': 2021}}, 'description': "Under this internship, a development and validation of LC-MS/MS methods for quantitative analysis of thyroid hormones T4, T3, RT3 and 3.5-T2 in cell lysate took place. The validation of the methods included parameters such as, matrix effects and the limits of detection and quantification. The main goal of this research was the optimization of the sample preparation using online SPE for the in order to achieve  LOQs low enough for THs in  50μ L of cell lysate to be able to be quantified (pg levels, <=0.3ng/m L ). The efficiency of offline SPE was also investigated.\nThe research was successfully completed and out of the three developed methods two will most likely be used in Vrije Universiteit's future research regarding thyroid hormone disruption.", 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Foteini', 'last_name': 'Eleftheriadou', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Analytical Chemist'}]}]
